20bd50d9-e1f1-4f72-a4bb-358d5d5e9e92.14a5a786-52c4-41e5-b648-ae850111b94c.description=
Compares two strings, returning a true response if and only if they contain the same sequence of characters. A null string is considered to be equal to an empty string.

Inputs\:
    string1 - The first string. 
Default value\: "" (empty)
    string2 - The second string.
Default value\: "" (empty)
    ignoreCase - If set to 'true', then the comparison ignores case considerations. The two strings are considered equal ignoring case if they are of the same length and corresponding characters in the two strings are equal ignoring case. If set to any value other than 'true', then the strings must match exactly to be considered equal.

Responses\:
    true - If the two strings are equal.
    false - If the two strings are not equal.
20bd50d9-e1f1-4f72-a4bb-358d5d5e9e92.57fdb03a-91dc-47f8-aae3-17a600713854.description=
Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults". As a result, the context key whose name is in the keyName input will be appended with the string from the input resultText.

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Returns\:
The value of the context variable it appended to.

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);

This operation does not do anything. It can be used to filter flow variables by defining them as inputs and filtering them in the Results tab.

Inputs\:
    field1 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field2 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field3 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field4 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of  "field1" as it was specified at input or when filtered. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
20bd50d9-e1f1-4f72-a4bb-358d5d5e9e92.849f7672-fc22-4866-b050-e7bf3f0d80f6.description=
Checks if a number or word is less than another number or word. Word comparison is case-sensitive in alphabetical order.

Inputs\:
value1 - The first value.
value2 - The second value.

Returns\:
value1 < value2

Responses\:
success - The boolean operation was evaluated to true.
failure - Something went wrong or the boolean operation returned false.

20bd50d9-e1f1-4f72-a4bb-358d5d5e9e92.d9b9ed70-2c54-4c6e-982d-7e303dcf0cee.description=
Resolves any flow variables in a String. This is useful if you have an input to a flow that references undefined flow variables, and define them later. Pass in the flow variable key name of the string that contains unresolved flow variables.

Inputs\:
keyName - The name of the flow variable that should have its value reresolved.
eraseUnresolved - A boolean value. If true, any unresolved flow variable references will be replaced by nothing (IE ${variable} disappears).

Responses\:
success - One or more flow variables were replaced, or could not be resolved and were erased from the string.
failure - No flow variables were referenced in the string.

Returns\:
The resulting string having had flow variable references replaced with the resolved values.

Examples of usage \:

I .

Set flow variable \: fw_var \= ${systems}xyz${system}        
Set flow variable \: system \= text

Flow variable resolver \:

keyName \= fw_var                              
eraseUnresolved \= false

The response is success and the result is ${systems}xyztext. The "systems" flow varible does not exist but is not deleted.

I' ( I reversed )

Set flow variable \: system \= text
Set flow variable \: fw_var \= ${systems}xyz${system}        

Flow variable resolver \:

keyName \= fw_var                              
eraseUnresolved \= false

When executing the second Set Flow Variable step, OO sees that it can resolve ${system} and does this. By the time the execution reaches Flow Variable Resolver, fw_var is already ${systems}xyztext. And the operation cannot resolve any more variables so it fails.

II. 

Same as I, but eraseUnresolved is true.

The response is success and the result is xyztext. The systems flow variable does not exist and is deleted   

III. same as I,  but "system" flow variable does not exist.

The response is failure and the result is ${systems}xyz${system}. Both flow variables do not exist and are not deleted, failure occurs because nothing changed from the initial value.

IV. 

Set flow variables\:

- keyNames \= system,vs
- myValues \= vs,1234

Flow variable resolver\:
- keyName \= ${system}
- eraseUnresolved \= false

Although we suply ${system} as the value for keyName, when debugging we see that the Step Input value is actually "vs" ( similar to I', OO already resolves the variable, before it reaches the functionality of the operation ). The variable "vs" exists in the context with the value 1234, which is also returned in the result. However, "vs" does not contain any flow variable names, therefore is not changed in the operation itself. Subsequenlty, the operation fails.

20bd50d9-e1f1-4f72-a4bb-358d5d5e9e92.f48ec778-6f65-40c7-a3ca-efd3fd04deef.description=
 
Check to see if the value stored in a specified flow variable, denoted by key, is null.

Inputs\:
    keyName - The key to check, i.e. the name of the flow variable. 
    trimSpaces - If set on "true" then all the whitespaces will be removed from the value stored. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false

Returns\: 
    The value in the specified key, i.e. flow variable with all whitespaces removed.

Responses\:
    isNull - If the key is a null pointer, i.e. the flow variable doesn't have an assigned value.
    notNull - If some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned. 

Notes\: 
    1. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "true" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "isNull". 
    2. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "false" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "notNull". 
    3. If any other value than "true" or "false" is passed on "trimSpaces" input then the default value (false) will be used.
